ce:section.ce:para:
The practical usefulness of the immunosensor was evaluated by determining the endogenous content of the target protein in human serum samples collected from 5 different HF patients. The possible existence of a matrix effect was investigated by constructing a calibration plot upon dilution of the samples 2500 times with PBS (pH 7.4) and spiking with growing AXL standard concentrations from 25 to 250 pg mL−1. The slope values of the corresponding linear calibration plot obtained for these samples were not statistically different than the slope value of the calibration plot constructed with sAXL standard solution (Fig. 5
                        ). Therefore, it could be concluded that no apparent matrix effect occurred when serum samples were 2500 times diluted. Accordingly, the endogenous concentration of sAXL in serum could be determined simply by interpolating the Δi responses measured for the diluted samples into the calibration plot prepared with AXL standards (Fig. 5). The results are summarized in Table 1
                         and compared with those provided by a commercial ELISA kit using the same immunoreagents.
